Let $$P_i=[x_i,y_i]\in F\mathrm P^1,$$ $$i=1,\dots,4$$ be four distinct points for an arbitrary [[field|KÃ¶rper]] $$F.$$ The //cross-ratio// of the points is

$$
\crossratio(P_1,P_2,P_3,P_4)\coloneqq
\frac
{
\det\begin{pmatrix}x_1 &x_2\\ y_1 &y_2\end{pmatrix}
\det\begin{pmatrix}x_3 &x_4\\ y_3 &y_4\end{pmatrix}
}
{
\det\begin{pmatrix}x_2 &x_3\\ y_2 &y_3\end{pmatrix}
\det\begin{pmatrix}x_4 &x_1\\ y_4 &y_1\end{pmatrix}
}.
$$

If $$u_i=x_i/y_i$$ are [[affine coordinates|Affine coordinates]], we get

$$
\frac{(u_1-u_2)(u_3-u_4)}{(u_2-u_3)(u_4-u_1)}.
$$

Even if one of the points is at infinity, we can cancel infinities, which is justified by the definition.

!! Properties


* <div>
If $$f\colon F\mathrm P^1\to F\mathrm P^1$$ is a [[projective transformation|Projective transformation]] and $$P_1,P_2,P_3,P_4\in F\mathrm P^1$$ are distinct, then
$$
\crossratio(P_1,P_2,P_3,P_4)=\crossratio(f(P_1),f(P_2),f(P_3),f(P_4)).$$
</div>

* <div>
There exists a projective transformation that maps four distinct points $$P_1,P_2,P_3,P_4$$ on a line to four distinct points $$Q_1,Q_2,Q_3,Q_4$$ on the same or another line if and only if
$$
\crossratio(P_1,P_2,P_3,P_4)=\crossratio(Q_1,Q_2,Q_3,Q_4).
$$
</div>

* The cross-ratio $$\crossratio(P_1,P_2,P_3,P_4)$$ is the affine coordinate of the image of $$P_1$$ under the projective transformation that maps $$P_2,P_3,P_4$$ to the points with affine coordinates $$0,1,\infty.$$

* The cross ratio doesn't change if one exchanges two of the points and the other two.